<dl id="n36198h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36198h">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36198h"> 198(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ gallowsbirds <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36198h"><li>FW 534.36 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36198h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36198h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36198h">MS BL 47484b-430</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:169 <a name="rBd14" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd14">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd14.htm#n36198h">Draft: III&sect;3B.14</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">There <font color="green">[invention]</font> was nothing more nor less than a gibbet, of a very strange, uncouth, and unmatchable construction, far more efficacious, as <font color="green">[William the Testy]</font> boasted, than the stocks, for the punishment of poverty. &hellip; the culprit, instead of being suspended by the neck, according to venerable custom, was hoisted by the waistband and kept dangling and sprawling for an hour or two at a time &hellip; It is incredible how the little governor chuckled at beholding caitiff vagrants and sturdy beggars thus swinging by the crupper and cutting antic gambols in the air. He had a thousand pleasantries, and mirthful conceits to utter upon these occasions. He called them his dandelions&mdash;his wild-fowl&mdash;his high-fliers&mdash;his spread-eagles&mdash;his goshawks&mdash;his scarecrows&mdash;and, finally, his <mark>gallows-birds</mark>. <small> Washington Irving, <a name="WINY" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WINY"><cite title="source">A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker</cite></a> (ed. unknown) 164f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
